title: Seacoast Sunday roundup: DuBois kicks Marshwood girls past Biddeford
text: Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 11:16 PM By Staff reports Posted Oct. 10, 2015 at 11:16 PM » Social News BIDDEFORD, Maine — Natalie DuBois scored a pair of second-half goals and the Marshwood High School girls soccer team beat Biddeford, 5-1, on Saturday to secure its sixth straight win. The Hawks soared to 9-1 in Southern Maine Class A, good for third in the latest heal point standings. Marshwood scored four of its five goals in the second half, after Marin Smith’s goal gave the team a 1-0 lead at halftime. Second-half goals by DuBois, Natalie Herbold and Zoe Janetos kept the Tigers (2-8) at bay. MHS goalies Nathalie Clavette and Emily Robida combined for four saves in the win. BOYS SOCCER Marshwood 3, South Portland 3 SOUTH PORTLAND, Maine — The Hawks got goals from Eyob Bosse, Riley Dinsmore-Patch and Ryan Gould in this draw, which moved them to 5-3-3 overall in Southern Maine Class A. South Portland moved to 5-3-4. Marshwood goalie Sam Leathe made five saves. VOLLEYBALL St. Thomas 3, Portsmouth 0 DOVER — Brenna Chrisom reached 1,000 career assists and 500 career kills to highlight the St. Thomas Aquinas volleyball team's sweep of Portsmouth on Saturday in Division II. Chrisom finished with 18 assists and seven digs as the Saints won by scores of 25-13, 25-15, 25-7. Ashley Coneys had nine kills and seven aces, and Payton Hodsdon added eight kills. FIELD HOCKEY York 2, Kennebunk 1 KENNEBUNK, Maine — The defending Class B champion Wildcats (14-0) capped their second straight perfect season, and they did it with some late-game heroics. Working off a penalty corner with under 3 minutes to play, York’s Sydney Bouchard kept the ball in at the right side of the circle and fired a shot toward the cage. Teammate Alie Jones took a swing at the ball as it trickled past the goalie and across the goalmouth, and Izzy Bretz was home on the weak side to knock in the game-winner. The Wildcats took a 1-0 lead into halftime after Jones scored off an assist from Bretz. Kennebunk (9-3-1) scored an equalizer early in the second half and the teams remained deadlocked until Bretz’s goal with about 2:30 remaining. York will be the top seed in the upcoming Southern Maine Class B regional tournament. CROSS COUNTRY PCA sweeps Homecoming meet DOVER — Portsmouth Christian Academy won both the boys and girls races at Saturday’s Homecoming cross country meet. Epping and Newmarket also competed. PCA took the top two spots in the boys race, with Zach Hartman (17:37) winning and Jack Longo placing runner-up. Newmarket’s Nathan Belanger finished third. On the girls side, Delaney Kjendal was first for PCA with teammate Sarah Kaczynski following in third. Newmarket’s Emily Mastin took second place. Epping was led by Konrad Hodgman, who was fifth overall in the boys race. GOLF Quinn falls short in repeat bid In the final round of the Division I golf championship at Hanover Country Club, Winnacunnet’s Ryan Quinn saw his quest for a repeat title stopped by Bishop Guertin’s Tom Ethier, who rallied after starting the day six shots off the lead. Quinn — who was masterful on Thursday, carding a 70 for low medalist honors — shot an 80 Saturday and finished four strokes back. Ethier captured the title after winning a playoff hole against past champion Brandon Gillis. Quinn finished fourth overall. In Division II, leader James McKee of Windham, who shot a 70 himself on Thursday to build a big lead, cruised to the individual title at Breakfast Hill Golf Course in Greenland. Oyster River’s Ryan Coxen (third place) and Portsmouth’s Justin Grondahl (seventh) each earned top-10 medals. By Staff reports
